ITME Society. The authority for execution of the regulations and guidelines of ITME

2. ABOUT ORGANISATION
2.1 Established as a non-profit Industry body in 1980, India ITME Society serves as
a catalyst for Technological Excellence and today is the backbone of Textile
Engineering Industry in India.
Today, the Society has become the cornerstone of the textile & Textile
Technology industry, accelerating technological innovations & collectively
shaping the textile industry and positively impacting the future.
The Society has left no stones unturned in establishing itself as one of India's
most successful exhibition organizers with its principles based on trust,
consistency & collaboration.
2.2 ITME-AFRICA & M.E. 2023 (30th November to 2nd December2023) in Nairobi,
Kenya shall become the focal point and catalyst for economic growth,
employment generation and technology up-gradation in Kenya and other
countries in Africa.
This technology event business shall showcase the complete range of textile
technology and textile engineering with a total of 32 chapters. 4 broad categories
are covered Textile Technology, Engineering, Textile Products, Financial
institutions and other segments.
With the prime motive of bringing highly modern and up-to-date Textile
Technology to Africa and offer prosperity by empowering textiles through trade
& new technologies along with ancillary and allied industries, India ITME
Society welcomes you to the 2nd edition of the strategic International business
event ITME Africa & M.E. 2023.
2.3 MISSION & VISION
Mission
To initiate a new era towards self-reliance, socio-economic advancement &
empowerment in the Textile & textile Engineering Sector with International co-
operation for Africa & Middle East
Vision
To serve as a gateway and One Stop Solution for Textile Technology &
Engineering encompassing Education, Skill Development, Investment Joint
Ventures & Sourcing.

6. ENTRY TO THE EVENT
6.1 The location and site plans of the Exhibition ground are given in the brochure.
During the event, exhibitors can enter the exhibition hall 1 hour before opening
time every day and they can exit one hour after the closing time on every day.
6.2 Trade and industry visitors, technicians, technical students, mill executives,
workmen, government representatives, representatives of financial sector and
other visitors are allowed entry on identity checked by the Exhibition Authority
from 09.00am hours to 5.00pm during the exhibition period.
6.3 Admission will be regulated during business hours, by pre-registration through
internet-App/e-invitation cards/on site-registration by presentation of
business/identity card/filling visitor registration form.
6.4 Children/students below 15 years of age will not be permitted entry to the
exhibition halls or exhibition area during setup days, show days & dismantling
days under any circumstances; even if they are accompanied by
exhibitor/parents/guardian.

7. EXHIBITION TARIFFS
Participations Charges & Guidelines for Booking Subsidy Eligibility
7.1 Shell scheme booth: US Dollars 375 per sqm (minimum booth size 9sqm) Shell
Scheme Stand Package for 9sqm: 2 chairs, 2 spotlights, one info desk, one socket
(1KW), fascia board, and one waste basket. And additional requirements for
furniture/ product display equipments etc. will have to be pre-booked at extra cost
from appointed vendors. (Shell stall Area 9sqm to 18sqm.)
7.2 No charges for open-side stalls, stall allocation will be done on the first-come-first-
served basis subject to receipt of 100% advance payment, open side stall will be
allocated subject to the availability in the layout plan.
7.3 Subsidy & special package if applicable shall open once you fill up online
application form as per your category / eligibility. Please follow the link:
www.itme-africa.com. Booking shall be confirmed once first Instalment is received
and allocation is on first come basis on 100% payment only.
7.4 Indian agent /consultant / distributor of Indian companies displaying
representing products manufactured in India shall pay in INR tariff.
7.5 Indian company shall fill national exhibitor form / Foreign companies shall fill
international exhibitor form. An undertaking confirming only domestic product
display is compulsory to qualify as national exhibitor and avail any subsidy ( is
provided.)
7.6 Indian agent / consultant / distributor displaying / product brochure or banners
representing foreign products/companies shall pay USD tariff.
7.7 Any Indian exhibitor who is promoting any products, goods, brochures of their
international partner or sister concern companies from abroad is liable to pay
their stall tariff/booking charges in USD.

10 STALL ALLOCATION
10.1 Allocation of the position and dimensions of the stalls will be decided by
the Exhibition Authority. stall allocation will be done on a first-come-first-
served basis subject to receipt of 100% advance payment. Open sides will be
allocated subject to availability in the layout plan.
10.2 The Exhibition Authority reserves the right to re-allocate the space allotted to
the exhibitor at any time prior to the commencement of the Exhibition,
should exceptional circumstances warrant such change to the location, size
and dimensions of the stall.
10.3 The Exhibition Authority further reserves the right to transfer or close
entrances and exits of the exhibition stalls and/or removes any of the proposed
amenities and undertakes any structural alterations. Such re-allocations will be
at the absolute discretion of the Exhibition Authority and the exhibitors shall
have no claim for compensation as a result of the re-allocation as above.

15 VENUE INFORMATION (The Kenyatta International Convention Center)
The Kenyatta International Convention Center is the leading facility in the meetings
industry in East Africa. Located at the heart of the central business district of Kenyas
Capital, KICC boasts of its proximity and easy accessibility to and from all major
five-star hotels, most of which are ten minutes walk away and five minutes away by
car. The center is PAD friendly with ramps that go throughout the center making it
accessible to all our guests.
Kenya can be accessed by road from Tanzania, Uganda, Ethiopia, Sudan and
Somalia. Migration ought to be handled at land outskirt stations.
15.1 Airport to Venue : By Air
Kenya has four international airports which include; Jomo Kenyatta International
Airport in Nairobi, Moi International Airport in Mombasa and Moi International
Airport in Eldoret, Kisumu International Airport.
These airports services numerous international carriers including the national
airline Kenya Airways. British Airways, Ethiopian airways, Kenya has good
Page 16 of 31
connections to destinations throughout Europe, the Asia- Pacific region, USA and
Africa
15.2 Taxi &amp; Hailing Apps
You can find most international taxi services in Kenya including uber, bolt and
others.
15.3 Rental Services
Most worldwide rental agencies have offices in Nairobi and Mombasa, and these
offer expensive but reliable cars with a full back-up network.

16 STALL DESIGN & CONSTRUCTION
16.1 All the exhibitors must submit and get approved their customized stall from the
Architect / design expert appointed by the Exhibition Authority on or before 5th
October 2023, as per Dos and Donts which will be intimated later.
Note : Considering that a period of 2 days has been provided in the pre
exhibition period for bringing in and installing exhibits which can be
displayed only in static mode. It is highly desirable on the part of the
exhibitors to plan arrival of exhibit cases well in advance at the KICC Hall,
Nairobi, Kenya. The exhibitors are also advised to discuss and plan their
schedules of bringing in exhibits with the approved clearing and forwarding
agents to ensure timely arrival of exhibits.
Page 17 of 31
16.2 The exhibitor is responsible for safety at the stand and for ensuring that
industrial safety and accident prevention regulations are complied with. The
exhibitor is liable for any damage that results from the construction or running
of his stand or the exhibits displayed in it. Conditions inside and outside the
halls as well as on the open-air site are similar to those on a building site
throughout the construction and dismantling periods. The personnel working
in this environment must be made aware of the dangers that exist.
16.3 To achieve uniformity in display and appearance of the entire exhibition and to
ensure proper presentation of all exhibits, Exhibitors are advised to strictly
follow the guidelines for stand construction, decoration and display specified
by the Organisers.
16.4 There would be general lighting within the hall. Temporary electrical
connection would be provided to carry on the construction work only from 0900
hrs to 1700 hrs. Aisles in the halls must be kept clear at all times, even during
the construction and dismantling periods since they are required as rescue and
escape routes. Construction material, empty packaging and exhibits are not
allowed to be stored in the aisles.
16.5 Exhibitors should leave minimum 30% of the stall area free for movement of
visitors.
16.6 To ensure safety of stall personnel and visitors, there should be no loose wiring
or hanging wires. All wiring must be carried out in PVC, Elastomeric or other
plastic sheathed cables. No exposed cable joints are permitted.
16.7 Sides, which are open to the aisles, should not be blocked by any opaque panels
more than 30% of the length of such side. Any structure, publicity material,
photographs, TV, Video Walls, Visuals, charts etc should not have height
exceeding 3.0 meters (bare space) and 2.5 meters (Shell stall). However, height
of products on display can be more than 2.5 meters.
16.8 The panels adjacent to other stand areas and the ceilings of the stand areas that
are visible from above must be properly finished in neutral colour without any
branding towards the adjacent stands. Electric wires must be covered by proper
casing. If this is not done, Organiser will carry out the necessary work and
charge all expenses to the defaulting exhibitors account.
16.9 The main supply points and electrical installations in the stand should be easily
accessible and should not be concealed / covered by the panels / partitions or
even by the exhibits.
Page 18 of 31
16.10 Logos can be displayed up to a height of 5.0 meters (for bare space) and 3.5
meters for shell stall exhibitors, provided they are away from adjacent stalls by
a minimum distance of 1 meter for stands with area up to 36 Sq. Mts and 2
meters for stands with area above 36 Sq. Mts.
16.11 Enclosures for office, conference or pantry can be set up in the stalls provided
the height and area covered by such enclosures is not more than 3.0 meters and
30% of the stall area respectively. Such enclosures should be located along the
building wall of the exhibition hall, if any, or at the rear of the stall. Enclosures
should be at least 2 meters away from the aisles.
16.12 For stands with 3 / 4 open sides, there shall be no partitions more than 30% on
the open sides and the inside partitions should also be such that they do not
obstruct the view or aesthetics of the adjoining stand/s. In case they are found
to be obstructive, such partitions shall have to be provided with clear glass /
acrylic above 1.2 meters height.
16.13 Use of suitable floor covering inside the stall, without damaging the floor is
recommended.
16.14 Use of loudspeakers, musical instruments etc. in the stalls is prohibited. Films,
multimedia presentations, video or slide shows on products, systems and
services may however be conducted within the stalls provided the sound level
is kept sufficiently low to avoid causing disturbance to others. Information
headphones are allowed, provided these are set up inside the stall at least 1
meter away from the aisles. Noisy demonstrations that may annoy other
exhibitors are forbidden. The noise level should not be more than 60 decibels,
measured at the stand limits.
16.15 Cellulose paints should not be sprayed on any type of object within the
Exhibition Halls. Use of exhibit materials that are dangerous, inflammable,
explosive, unhealthy, foul-smelling or which may, in general, annoy other
Exhibitors or visitors is not permitted. Use of spray painting for stall decoration
is not permitted within any hall. Organisers advise exhibitors to bring in
prefabricated stand to avoid delay in completion of stands as well as
inconvenience to other exhibitors.
16.16 Use of bright and/or coloured lights, neon signs of any size, shape or colour or
any other electrical decorative material is forbidden. Depicting exhibitors name
or logo in non flickering/non off-on type light is however permitted. Use of
cloth banner inside and outside the stall is strictly not allowed.
Page 19 of 31
16.17 Use of all types of publicity materials such as posters, banners, hanging
decorations made of any material is not allowed outside the stall area of the
exhibitors. Suspending of display items from the Hall ceiling or any other
structure falling within the stands is also not permitted.
16.18 Posters, banners, hangings and advertisement boards will be put up by the
Organisers and will be available as sponsorship opportunities for the exhibitors.

19 INFORMATION FOR INTENDING EXHIBITORS IN KENYA
19.1 ARRIVAL OF GOODS
19.1.1 Goods should be dispatched to arrive in Nairobi well before the show.
19.1.2 Goods dispatched by sea freight should be at port Mombasa 15 - 20 days before
the exhibition.
19.1.3 Goods dispatched by airfreight should arrive at Jomo Kenyatta International
Airport 10 days before the exhibition.
19.2 CONSIGNMENT OF GOODS
19.2.1 Goods being brought in temporarily should be shipped separately from
giveaways or promotional material.
19.2.2 Consignee details for both air and ocean (check with us) unless the exhibitor
has representation in Kenya and are registered.
19.3 DOCUMENTATION OF GOODS
19.3.1 Storage charges at Nairobi Airport are very high. We are allowed only 48hours
storage free period. Therefore, origin will be required to forward a copy of
invoice prior to dispatch to enable us to open an Import Declaration Form (IDF)
based on which supplier will contact one of the inspection agencies depending
on carry out Pre-Shipment Verification of Conformity (PVoC) and a Certificate
of Conformity issued.
Page 21 of 31
The inspection agencies are:
19.3.1 China Certification & Inspection Group Company Ltd
19.3.2 China Hansom Inspection & Certificate Co. Ltd
19.3.3 Societe Generale de Surveillance S.A
19.3.4 TUV Austria (Turk) Kenya Limited
19.3.6 World Standardization Certification & Testing Group (Shenzhen) Co. Ltd
NOTE: Goods shipped without a Certificate of Conformity (CoC) will be
subjected to destination inspection at 5% of the customs value. In case the
shipment is subjected to further testing, the additional testing charges will be
on account of the exhibitor. Goods found not to conform with the standards will
be shipped back to country of origin or destroyed at importers expense. Note:
All food products will be subjected to sampling, testing/analysis and shall not
be allowed to clear until the test results are out and products found fit for
human consumption.
19.3.7 All goods shipped should be accompanied by the following documents:-
A. Certificate of Conformity (CoC) issued by one of the inspection
agencies as listed in above. Date of CoC issuance must be prior
to freight arrival.
B. Copy of Sea waybill or express bill of lading / AWB
C. Commercial Invoice / packing list in ENGLISH
19.4 The invoice should include the following details:-
19.4.1 Itemized and detailed description of all goods showing FOB value, quantity
(qty like 1 lot, 1 box, are not acceptable), unit of measure ( pcs, pairs, sets etc)
per item, cost and freight (separately ( in case of CFR shipments ), country of
origin and manufacture, whether new or used. Note: CIF is not allowed on the
CI. If insurance is required, this MUST be obtained from an insurance company
that is registered in Kenya.
19.4.2 The relative HTS# if known. (This will assist us with declaration) 15.4.3 All
values should be shown if possible in either US Dollar, Euro or Sterling Pounds
although most currencies are permitted
19.4.3 Full particulars of the shipper including tel/fax numbers and a contact name.
Page 22 of 31
19.4.4 In the case of machinery or equipment serial and model numbers, and date of
manufacture should be shown.
19.5 PACKING OF GOODS
19.5.1 To avoid damage, all goods should be in substantial packing.
19.5.2 Goods for display (return exhibits) and goods for giveaways or promotional
material should be in separate boxes. These must also be shipped under
separate paperwork. (AWB and Commercial Invoice)
19.6 CUSTOMS PROCEDURES
19.6.1 A. Goods shipped into Kenya fall into two main categories:-
B. Goods for temporary exhibition and return
C. Promotional material and giveaways that are intended to
remain in Kenya.
19.6.2 Temporary Imports Items MUST have identifying marks and
numbers to be allowed to clear on temporary imports
A. We will be required to seek permission from customs to import good
on temporary basis. For this we will require a copy of the commercial
invoice, which must indicate the serial number against each item. We
would also require a letter from the organizers confirming exhibitors
participation.
B. We will be required to process security bond with Customs to cover the
amount of duty and VAT otherwise payable on these items.
C. All goods entered under Temporary Import remain under our control
during the show and will be moved to our premises after the show. It is
possible that orders will be received for various exhibits. These MUST
not be released to the buyers until we complete the customs procedures
for conversion into home use.
19.7 CUSTOMS PENALTIES
19.7.1 Heavy penalties and confiscation of shipment are imposed for misdeclaration,
undervaluation of goods or due to lack of proper documentation.
Page 23 of 31
19.7.2 The penalties may be imposed for any one of the
following:-
A incorrect description of goods
B Failure to detail all goods
C Undervaluation of goods
D Importing without advice on restricted goods
E Importing banned goods
F Shipping more quantity than declared on the invoice
19.8 VALUATION OF GOODS
19.8.1 If it is hoped to sell any goods on display it is in your interest to value goods
correctly
19.8.2 Failure to do so may cause considerable problems with
A. Processing an IDF
B. Clearing the goods through Customs
C. Return of goods not sold Freight charges in case of sea
freight form part of the Customs dutiable value. The
commercial invoice should therefore be issued as CFR and
a breakup of Cost and freight shown separately, or the bill
of lading to be rated, otherwise, freight would be calculated
at 18.5% of the FOB value.
19.9 CARGO INFORMATION
Please note that exhibition cargo is not a responsibility of the organizers.
Information below is for your assistance only. You may deal directly with the
agents listed below or your regular forwarding agent in your country who has a
counterpart in Kenya.
If the samples are not bulky, exhibitors are advised to carry them as personal
baggage. This will save money as sending air / sea cargo is more expensive than
paying for extra baggage.
All exhibitors must send a sample invoice / packing list before shipping / air
freighting the goods, by email / fax to the clearing agents to get an approximate
value of all charges involved and advice on values declared. Exhibitors must
write to all Clearing Agents for guidelines on all documents required, which may
include Invoice, Packing List, Certificate of Origin, appropriate certificates for
food, medical, restricted and prohibited goods.
The exhibitors must pay cargo charges directly or through their forwarding
agents, by telex transfer or by cash, in Nairobi, prior to receiving the goods. The
clearing agents may not release your goods to you otherwise. Goods are usually
provided to exhibitor's stands unless advised differently.
Page 24 of 31
Goods should not be much under-invoiced as customs may put their own value,
if not satisfied with the invoice value declared by the exhibitor. Please consult
the clearing agents for their advice, if necessary.
For promotional items such as brochures, small giveaways, display stands etc.,
please declare a small value.
All goods should reach the port at least 15 days and airport at least 10 days prior
to the opening of the exhibition, to ensure that the goods are cleared in time.
Exhibition samples and stand construction materials should be packed and
declared separately from goods for test sales.
A small advice to all exhibitors worldwide is to always carry some brochures /
business cards / posters etc. as hand baggage so that they are not empty handed
at their stand, if their cargo or personal baggage is delayed / lost etc. It is
important that all precautions are taken to ensure that your investment is not
wasted.
Exhibitors should note that India ITME Society will not pay any duties/ taxes
declared for their goods. Also, all duties and taxes are fixed by the Government
and are non-negotiable.
